### Example 8: Ratio as a Fraction on a Pie (Conceptual)

<!-- BUILD: Given two quantities, compute the fraction each represents of the total. Print both fractions. (We'll draw pie charts when we get to probability—just print for now.) -->

```scheme
(define boys 12)
(define girls 18)
(define total (+ boys girls))

(define boys-fraction (exact/rat boys total))
(define girls-fraction (exact/rat girls total))

(print \"Boys: \" boys \" out of \" total \" = \" (exact/->string boys-fraction))
(print \"Girls: \" girls \" out of \" total \" = \" (exact/->string girls-fraction))
(print \"As decimals: \" (exact/->float boys-fraction) \" and \" (exact/->float girls-fraction))
```

[VISUAL: Printed fractions—boys 12/30 = 2/5 = 0.4, girls 18/30 = 3/5 = 0.6]

---

### Example 9: Comparing Ratios (Which Mixture Is Redder?)

<!-- BUILD: Two paint mixtures with different ratios of red to yellow. Compare which has a higher proportion of red. -->

```scheme
(define mix-a-red 5)
(define mix-a-yellow 3)

(define mix-b-red 7)
(define mix-b-yellow 5)

(define ratio-a (exact/rat mix-a-red (+ mix-a-red mix-a-yellow)))
(define ratio-b (exact/rat mix-b-red (+ mix-b-red mix-b-yellow)))

(print \"Mix A: \" mix-a-red \" red, \" mix-a-yellow \" yellow -> red proportion: \" (exact/->string ratio-a))
(print \"Mix B: \" mix-b-red \" red, \" mix-b-yellow \" yellow -> red proportion: \" (exact/->string ratio-b))

(if (exact/> ratio-a ratio-b)
    (print \"Mix A is redder.\")
    (print \"Mix B is redder.\"))
```

[VISUAL: Printed comparison showing Mix A is 5/8 red, Mix B is 7/12 red; 5/8 > 7/12, so A is redder]

---

### Example 10: Ratio Table (Scaling Up and Down)

<!-- BUILD: Given a base ratio (2:3), generate a table of equivalent ratios by scaling by 1, 2, 3, 4, 5. Print the table. -->

```scheme
(define base-a 2)
(define base-b 3)

(define (make-row scale)
  (list scale (* base-a scale) (* base-b scale)))

(define table (map make-row (list 1 2 3 4 5)))

(print \"Ratio \" base-a \":\" base-b \" scaled:\")
(map (lambda (row)
       (print \"  x\" (car row) \" -> \" (cadr row) \":\" (caddr row)))
     table)
```

[VISUAL: Printed table showing x1 -> 2:3, x2 -> 4:6, x3 -> 6:9, x4 -> 8:12, x5 -> 10:15]

---

### Example 11: Density as a Unit Rate (Mass Per Volume)

<!-- BUILD: Compute density (grams per cubic centimeter). Print the unit rate. -->

```scheme
(define mass-grams 150)
(define volume-cm3 50)

(define density (exact/rat mass-grams volume-cm3))

(print \"Mass: \" mass-grams \" grams\")
(print \"Volume: \" volume-cm3 \" cubic centimeters\")
(print \"Density: \" (exact/->float density) \" grams per cubic centimeter\")
```

[VISUAL: Printed output showing density = 3.0 g/cm³]

---

### Example 12: Ratio on a Scatter Plot (Height vs. Age Data)

<!-- BUILD: Plot several (age, height) points. The ratio isn't constant (kids grow at different rates), but we can see the trend. Use plot/scatter. -->

```scheme
(define data (list (list 7 48)
                   (list 8 51)
                   (list 9 54)
                   (list 10 56)
                   (list 11 59)
                   (list 12 62)))

(define p (plot/scatter data
                        #:x-label \"Age (years)\"
                        #:y-label \"Height (inches)\"
                        #:title \"Height vs. Age\"))

(print (plot/render-svg p 400 300))
```

[VISUAL: Scatter plot showing age on x-axis (7-12), height on y-axis (48-62), points roughly linear but not a perfect ratio (growth rate varies)]

Not every relationship is a clean ratio—real data is messy—but when points lie on a straight line through the origin, the relationship *is* proportional.

