## Topic 2: Proportional Relationships and Solving Proportions

### Gentle Opening: When Two Quantities Grow Together

A relationship is **proportional** if one quantity is always a constant multiple of the other. If you drive at a steady speed, distance is proportional to time (distance = speed × time). Double the time, double the distance. The hallmark of a proportional relationship: its graph is a straight line through the origin.

A **proportion** is an equation stating that two ratios are equal: a/b = c/d. Cross-multiplication (a×d = b×c) is the ancient technique for solving proportions—Babylonian scribes used it 4,000 years ago.

Proportions appear in scale models (a 1:24 model car means every inch on the model represents 24 inches on the real car), map scales (1 cm = 10 km), and any time you say \"if this much costs that much, how much does twice as much cost?\"

In Motoi, proportional relationships are *scaling*: if this design is 3 inches wide at 5 inches tall, how tall should it be at 6 inches wide to keep the same proportions? On the canvas, proportional scaling keeps shapes similar—every length multiplied by the same factor.

---

### Example 13: Recognizing a Proportional Relationship (Table)

<!-- BUILD: Given a table of (x, y) pairs where y = 3x, print the table and note that the ratio y/x is constant. -->

```scheme
(define data (list (list 1 3)
                   (list 2 6)
                   (list 3 9)
                   (list 4 12)
                   (list 5 15)))

(print \"x\\ty\\ty/x\")
(map (lambda (pair)
       (let ((x (car pair))
             (y (cadr pair)))
         (print x \"\\t\" y \"\\t\" (exact/->float (exact/rat y x)))))
     data)

(print \"The ratio y/x is always 3.0 -> proportional relationship.\")
```

[VISUAL: Printed table showing x, y, and y/x; every row has y/x = 3.0]

---

### Example 14: Graphing a Proportional Relationship (y = kx)

<!-- BUILD: Plot the line y = 2.5x from x=0 to x=10. Use plot/function. The line passes through the origin. -->

```scheme
(define k 2.5)

(define f (lambda (x) (* k x)))

(define p (plot/function f 0 10
                         #:y-label \"y\"
                         #:x-label \"x\"
                         #:title \"y = 2.5x (proportional)\"))

(print (plot/render-svg p 400 300))
```

[VISUAL: Straight line from (0,0) through (10,25), passing through the origin—the signature of a proportional relationship]

---

### Example 15: Non-Proportional Relationship (Line Not Through Origin)

<!-- BUILD: Plot y = 2x + 3. It's linear but NOT proportional (doesn't pass through origin). -->

```scheme
(define f (lambda (x) (+ (* 2 x) 3)))

(define p (plot/function f 0 10
                         #:y-label \"y\"
                         #:x-label \"x\"
                         #:title \"y = 2x + 3 (linear but not proportional)\"))

(print (plot/render-svg p 400 300))
```

[VISUAL: Straight line from (0,3) onward—linear, but because it doesn't pass through (0,0), the relationship is NOT proportional]

---

### Example 16: Solving a Proportion (Cross-Multiplication by Hand)

<!-- BUILD: Solve 3/4 = x/12 for x. Cross-multiply: 3×12 = 4×x, so x = 36/4 = 9. Print the solution. -->

```scheme
(define a 3)
(define b 4)
(define c 'x)  ; unknown
(define d 12)

; Cross-multiply: a * d = b * x
; x = (a * d) / b

(define x (exact// (exact/* (exact/rat a 1) (exact/rat d 1))
                   (exact/rat b 1)))

(print \"Proportion: \" a \"/\" b \" = x/\" d)
(print \"Cross-multiply: \" a \" * \" d \" = \" b \" * x\")
(print \"x = (\" a \" * \" d \") / \" b \" = \" (exact/->string x))
```

[VISUAL: Printed solution showing x = 9/1 = 9]

---

### Example 17: Solving a Proportion (Using exact/ Division)

<!-- BUILD: Solve 5/8 = 15/y for y. Rearrange: y = (8 * 15) / 5. Print the solution. -->

```scheme
(define a 5)
(define b 8)
(define c 15)
(define d 'y)

; a / b = c / y
; y = (b * c) / a

(define y (exact// (exact/* (exact/rat b 1) (exact/rat c 1))
                   (exact/rat a 1)))

(print \"Proportion: \" a \"/\" b \" = \" c \"/y\")
(print \"y = (\" b \" * \" c \") / \" a \" = \" (exact/->string y))
```

[VISUAL: Printed solution showing y = 120/5 = 24]

