### Example 39: Probability as a Number Between 0 and 1

<!-- BUILD: Print several probabilities and note that they're all between 0 (impossible) and 1 (certain). -->

```scheme
(define impossible (exact/rat 0 1))
(define unlikely (exact/rat 1 10))
(define even-chance (exact/rat 1 2))
(define likely (exact/rat 9 10))
(define certain (exact/rat 1 1))

(print \"Probability scale:\")
(print \"  Impossible: \" (exact/->float impossible))
(print \"  Unlikely (10%): \" (exact/->float unlikely))
(print \"  Even chance (50%): \" (exact/->float even-chance))
(print \"  Likely (90%): \" (exact/->float likely))
(print \"  Certain: \" (exact/->float certain))
(print \"All probabilities are between 0 and 1.\")
```

[VISUAL: Printed scale from 0.0 to 1.0 with labels]

---

### Example 40: Complement of an Event (NOT Rolling a 6)

<!-- BUILD: P(not 6) = 1 - P(6). Compute and print. -->

```scheme
(define total-outcomes 6)
(define favorable-for-6 1)

(define prob-6 (exact/rat favorable-for-6 total-outcomes))
(define prob-not-6 (exact/- (exact/rat 1 1) prob-6))

(print \"P(rolling a 6): \" (exact/->string prob-6))
(print \"P(NOT rolling a 6): \" (exact/->string prob-not-6))
```

[VISUAL: Printed output showing P(6) = 1/6, P(not 6) = 5/6]

The complement rule: P(not A) = 1 − P(A).

---

### Example 41: Experimental Probability (Simulated Coin Flips)

<!-- BUILD: Simulate 100 coin flips (random 0 or 1, 0=Heads, 1=Tails). Count heads. Compute experimental probability. Print it alongside theoretical (0.5). -->

```scheme
(define n-flips 100)

; Simulate flips (we'll use modulo of a pseudorandom-ish counter for simplicity)
(define (flip i) (modulo (* i 7919) 2))  ; a simple pseudo-rng

(define flips (map flip (range 1 (+ n-flips 1))))
(define heads-count (length (filter (lambda (f) (= f 0)) flips)))

(define experimental-prob (exact/->float (exact/rat heads-count n-flips)))

(print \"Simulated \" n-flips \" coin flips.\")
(print \"Heads: \" heads-count)
(print \"Experimental probability of heads: \" experimental-prob)
(print \"Theoretical probability: 0.5\")
```

[VISUAL: Printed output showing experimental probability close to but not exactly 0.5 (e.g. 0.48 or 0.51)]

Experimental probability is *observed frequency*. As the number of trials grows, it converges toward the theoretical probability (the **Law of Large Numbers**).

---

### Example 42: Probability Histogram (Die Rolls)

<!-- BUILD: Simulate 60 rolls of a fair die. Tally how many times each face appears. Plot a histogram. -->

```scheme
(define n-rolls 60)

; Simulate die rolls (pseudo-rng mod 6, shift to 1..6)
(define (roll i) (+ 1 (modulo (* i 7919) 6)))

(define rolls (map roll (range 1 (+ n-rolls 1))))

; Tally counts for each face (1..6)
(define (count-face face rolls)
  (length (filter (lambda (r) (= r face)) rolls)))

(define counts (map (lambda (face) (list face (count-face face rolls)))
                    (list 1 2 3 4 5 6)))

(define p (plot/bar counts
                    #:x-label \"Die face\"
                    #:y-label \"Count\"
                    #:title \"60 Die Rolls (Simulated)\"))

(print \"Simulated \" n-rolls \" die rolls:\")
(map (lambda (c) (print \"  Face \" (car c) \": \" (cadr c) \" times\")) counts)
(print (plot/render-svg p 400 300))
```

[VISUAL: Bar chart with 6 bars (one per die face), heights showing the count for each face. Should be roughly equal (around 10 each), but with random variation.]

Each face *should* appear about 10 times (60/6 = 10), but randomness means some will be higher, some lower. With more rolls, the bars even out.

---

### Example 43: Probability of \"Or\" (Mutually Exclusive Events)

<!-- BUILD: On a die, P(1 or 2) = P(1) + P(2). Compute and print. -->

```scheme
(define total-outcomes 6)

(define prob-1 (exact/rat 1 total-outcomes))
(define prob-2 (exact/rat 1 total-outcomes))

(define prob-1-or-2 (exact/+ prob-1 prob-2))

(print \"P(rolling a 1): \" (exact/->string prob-1))
(print \"P(rolling a 2): \" (exact/->string prob-2))
(print \"P(rolling a 1 OR a 2): \" (exact/->string prob-1-or-2))
```

[VISUAL: Printed output showing P(1 or 2) = 1/6 + 1/6 = 2/6 = 1/3]

When events are **mutually exclusive** (can't both happen), P(A or B) = P(A) + P(B).

---

### Example 44: Probability of \"And\" (Independent Events—Two Coin Flips)

<!-- BUILD: Flip two coins. P(both heads) = P(H on first) * P(H on second) = 1/2 * 1/2 = 1/4. Print it. -->

```scheme
(define prob-heads-1 (exact/rat 1 2))
(define prob-heads-2 (exact/rat 1 2))

(define prob-both-heads (exact/* prob-heads-1 prob-heads-2))

(print \"P(heads on first flip): \" (exact/->string prob-heads-1))
(print \"P(heads on second flip): \" (exact/->string prob-heads-2))
(print \"P(both heads): \" (exact/->string prob-both-heads))
```

[VISUAL: Printed output showing P(HH) = 1/2 * 1/2 = 1/4]

When events are **independent** (one doesn't affect the other), P(A and B) = P(A) × P(B).

---

### Example 45: Sample Space for Two Dice (Counting Outcomes)

<!-- BUILD: List all 36 outcomes when rolling two dice. Print a few, and the total count. -->

```scheme
(define die-1 (list 1 2 3 4 5 6))
(define die-2 (list 1 2 3 4 5 6))

(define outcomes
  (apply append
         (map (lambda (d1)
                (map (lambda (d2) (list d1 d2)) die-2))
              die-1)))

(print \"Sample space for two dice (36 outcomes):\")
(print \"First few: \" (take outcomes 6))
(print \"Total: \" (length outcomes))
```

[VISUAL: Printed output showing first few outcomes like (1,1), (1,2), (1,3)..., total 36]

