## Topic 5: Angles, Circles, and Area

### Gentle Opening: The Geometry of Turning and Enclosing

Seventh grade revisits geometry with new precision. You've drawn shapes since kindergarten; now you *measure* them. **Angles** are amounts of turning—a quarter-turn is 90°, a half-turn 180°, a full turn 360°. **Circles** are the set of all points equidistant from a center—perfectly symmetric, perfectly round. **Area** is how much space a shape encloses.

Angles were formalized by ancient Greek astronomers (the degree, 1/360 of a circle, may come from the Babylonian calendar of ~360 days). Circles fascinated mathematicians for millennia—Euclid proved that the ratio of circumference to diameter is constant (we call it π, though the Greeks didn't have that symbol). Archimedes computed π to remarkable precision by inscribing polygons in circles.

Area formulas (rectangle, triangle, circle) let you quantify space. Builders use them to estimate materials. Farmers use them to measure fields. Biologists use them to estimate populations (sample a small area, scale up). On the canvas, area is the count of dots inside a boundary—draw a circle, fill it, count the pixels, compare to πr².

In this topic we'll measure angles (degrees and radians), compute circumference and area of circles, and find areas of composite shapes by breaking them into rectangles and triangles.

---

### Example 51: Angle Measurement (Degrees)

<!-- BUILD: Define several angles in degrees. Print them. -->

```scheme
(define right-angle 90)
(define straight-angle 180)
(define full-rotation 360)
(define acute-angle 45)
(define obtuse-angle 120)

(print \"Angles in degrees:\")
(print \"  Right angle: \" right-angle \"°\")
(print \"  Straight angle: \" straight-angle \"°\")
(print \"  Full rotation: \" full-rotation \"°\")
(print \"  Acute angle: \" acute-angle \"°\")
(print \"  Obtuse angle: \" obtuse-angle \"°\")
```

[VISUAL: Printed list of angle measures]

An **acute** angle is less than 90°, a **right** angle is exactly 90°, an **obtuse** angle is between 90° and 180°, a **straight** angle is 180°.

---

### Example 52: Converting Degrees to Radians

<!-- BUILD: Convert 90°, 180°, 360° to radians using geom/->radians. Print the results. -->

```scheme
(define deg-90 90)
(define deg-180 180)
(define deg-360 360)

(print deg-90 \"° = \" (geom/->radians deg-90) \" radians\")
(print deg-180 \"° = \" (geom/->radians deg-180) \" radians\")
(print deg-360 \"° = \" (geom/->radians deg-360) \" radians\")
```

[VISUAL: Printed output showing 90° ≈ 1.571 rad (π/2), 180° ≈ 3.142 rad (π), 360° ≈ 6.283 rad (2π)]

**Radians** are another way to measure angles. A full circle is 2π radians. Radians are \"natural\" because they relate the angle to the arc length on a unit circle.

---

### Example 53: Angles in a Triangle Sum to 180°

<!-- BUILD: Given two angles of a triangle, compute the third using the fact that the sum is 180°. Print the result. -->

```scheme
(define angle-a 50)
(define angle-b 60)
(define angle-c (- 180 (+ angle-a angle-b)))

(print \"Triangle angles: \" angle-a \"°, \" angle-b \"°, \" angle-c \"°\")
(print \"Sum: \" (+ angle-a angle-b angle-c) \"°\")
```

[VISUAL: Printed output showing angles 50°, 60°, 70°, sum 180°]

This is one of Euclid's classic theorems—the interior angles of any triangle sum to 180°.

---

### Example 54: Circle Circumference (C = 2πr)

<!-- BUILD: Given radius 5, compute circumference using geom/circle-circumference. Print it. -->

```scheme
(define radius 5)
(define circumference (geom/circle-circumference radius))

(print \"Circle with radius \" radius)
(print \"Circumference: \" circumference)
```

[VISUAL: Printed output showing C ≈ 31.416]

The circumference is the distance around the circle. The formula C = 2πr (or πd, where d is diameter) has been known for thousands of years.

---

### Example 55: Circle Area (A = πr²)

<!-- BUILD: Given radius 5, compute area using geom/circle-area. Print it. -->

```scheme
(define radius 5)
(define area (geom/circle-area radius))

(print \"Circle with radius \" radius)
(print \"Area: \" area)
```

[VISUAL: Printed output showing A ≈ 78.540]

---

### Example 56: Comparing Circumference and Area (Different Radii)

<!-- BUILD: Compute circumference and area for radii 1, 2, 3, 4, 5. Print a table. -->

```scheme
(define radii (list 1 2 3 4 5))

(print \"r\\tC\\tA\")
(map (lambda (r)
       (let ((c (geom/circle-circumference r))
             (a (geom/circle-area r)))
         (print r \"\\t\" (round (* c 100)) \"/100\\t\" (round (* a 100)) \"/100\")))
     radii)
```

[VISUAL: Printed table showing how circumference and area grow with radius]

Area grows with r², so it increases faster than circumference (which grows with r).

---

### Example 57: Semicircle Area

<!-- BUILD: A semicircle is half a circle. Compute area of a semicircle with radius 6. -->

```scheme
(define radius 6)
(define full-area (geom/circle-area radius))
(define semi-area (/ full-area 2))

(print \"Semicircle with radius \" radius)
(print \"Area: \" semi-area)
```

[VISUAL: Printed output showing area ≈ 56.549 (half of πr²)]

